The paper proposes a variant of the Count-Min Sketch algorithm, which is widely used in large-scale processing for approximate event counting. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Additionally, the paper addresses the issue of low-frequency items in text mining tasks, which suggests that it could also belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. The proposed algorithm aims to improve the average relative error of CMS, which is a common problem in approximate counting, indicating that it could also belong to the Databases (cs.DB) sub-category. The use of logarithm-based, approximate counters suggests that the paper could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, as it involves machine learning techniques. Finally, the paper proposes a new algorithm that improves the performance of an existing one, which could also make it relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
